# gen39: grounded verbalization -- reasoning turned back into language.
# "describe <x>" generates a sentence for every class x is *provably* a member
# of, including beliefs reached only through rules. Contrast with "what do you
# know about <x>?", which reports stored facts only. The content is grounded in
# real KB state, not canned; facts arrive via the gen32 reader. Held-out tokens.
> read: tariq is a knight. every knight is a noble. every noble is a person.
< Learned 3 fact(s), skipped 0.
# Generation speaks the derived beliefs (noble, person) too, not just the fact.
> describe tariq
< tariq is a knight. tariq is a noble. tariq is a person.
# The direct-fact report stays shallow -- only what is stored.
> what do you know about tariq?
< tariq is a knight.
# Nothing provable -> nothing said, no invention.
> describe ghost
< I have nothing to say about ghost.